 (of Norman origin): either a nickname from Old French <i>picon</i> ‘woodpecker’ or a patronymic from the Old French personal name <i>Picon</i>, apparently a transferred use of Old French <i>picon</i> ‘point, pointed object’ as a nickname. Compare   Pickett   and   Pike  . The Scottish surname (first recorded in 1615 in Edinburgh) was taken to Ireland, where in 1796 it is recorded as <i>Picken</i> in Antrim and <i>Pickens</i> in Cavan. See   Pickens  .","German: probably a variant of   Pick   1 or 2."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":43,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Emma Piking was born in 1412, in Fleet Marston, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Ralph Verney - Lord Mayor of London about 1435, in Fleet Marston, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were th